{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is the key-derivation algorithm itself (normalization, ordering, serialization, hashing). No real I/O is required, and mocks are unnecessary because inputs/outputs can be exercised directly with deterministic and property-based cases.","test_description":"Test the key-generation function/object directly with many parameter permutations: same logical params in different orders produce identical keys; different params produce different keys across a large randomized corpus. Include edge cases (nulls, arrays, unicode, numeric/string distinctions) to catch canonicalization bugs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is rule-to-TTL mapping logic (plus any clock arithmetic). This is deterministic and local; a mock would not hide correctness issues if real config values are passed in-memory.","test_description":"Exercise TTL computation with real rule objects for each category and boundary values (unknown category fallback, zero/negative misconfig handling, time rounding). Assert exact TTL outputs in seconds/ms for each configured freshness rule.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"If switching depends on real process memory pressure/OS-reported usage, in-process mocks can hide threshold and sampling behavior bugs. Minimum reliable boundary is exercising the real memory signal path end-to-end.","test_description":"Run the cache in a real process, configure a low/high memory threshold, drive allocations to cross threshold, and assert observed strategy transitions (LRU -> LFU) via metrics/log hooks. Include hysteresis/flap checks around the threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.34,"System":0.58,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is module wiring between DB write path/change detection and cache invalidation logic. A pure mock can miss SQL/filter/key-mapping mismatches; using a real local Postgres instance catches these without requiring full system scope.","test_description":"Start cache + data access modules against a local Postgres test DB. Seed rows and corresponding cached entries, perform INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE on target rows, then assert matching keys are invalidated and non-matching keys remain. Verify behavior across transaction commit boundaries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.24,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Correctness depends on interaction between access tracking and eviction execution across cache components. Unit tests on policy internals help, but can miss real wiring bugs (e.g., recency/frequency counters not updated by actual read/write paths).